columns.name: ExperienceRange
columns.expression:
SWITCH(
    TRUE(),
    RHContratos[AnosNaEmpresa] < 1, "0-1 Year",
    RHContratos[AnosNaEmpresa] >= 1 && RHContratos[AnosNaEmpresa] < 3, "1-3 Years",
    RHContratos[AnosNaEmpresa] >= 3 && RHContratos[AnosNaEmpresa] < 5, "3-5 Years",
    RHContratos[AnosNaEmpresa] >= 5 && RHContratos[AnosNaEmpresa] < 10, "5-10 Years",
    RHContratos[AnosNaEmpresa] >= 10, "10+ Years",
    "Unknown"
)

columns.name: AnosNaEmpresa
columns.expression:
DATEDIFF(RHContratos[DataContratacao], TODAY(), YEAR) - 
    IF(
        FORMAT(RHContratos[DataContratacao], "MMDD") > FORMAT(TODAY(), "MMDD"),
        1,
        0
    )

rules_violated.name: [Performance] Model should have a date table
rules_violated.description: Generally speaking, models should generally have a date table. Models that do not have a date table generally are not taking advantage of features such as time intelligence or may not have a properly structured architecture.

rules_violated.name: [Maintenance] Ensure tables have relationships
rules_violated.description: This rule highlights tables which are not connected to any other table in the model with a relationship.

rules_violated.name: [Performance] Reduce number of calculated columns
rules_violated.description:
Calculated columns do not compress as well as data columns so they take up more memory. They also slow down processing times for both the table as well as process recalc. Offload calculated column logic to your data warehouse and turn these calculated columns into data columns.
Reference: https://www.elegantbi.com/post/top10bestpractices

rules_violated.name: [Formatting] Relationship columns should be of integer data type
rules_violated.description: It is a best practice for relationship columns to be of integer data type. This applies not only to data warehousing but data modeling as well.

rules_violated.name: [DAX Expressions] Use the DIVIDE function for division
rules_violated.description:
Use the DIVIDE  function instead of using "/". The DIVIDE function resolves divide-by-zero cases. As such, it is recommended to use to avoid errors.

Reference: https://docs.microsoft.com/power-bi/guidance/dax-divide-function-operator

rules_violated.name: [Maintenance] Visible objects with no description
rules_violated.description:
Add descriptions to objects. These descriptions are shown on hover within the Field List in Power BI Desktop. Additionally, you can leverage these descriptions to create an automated data dictionary (see link below).
Reference: https://www.elegantbi.com/post/datadictionary

rules_violated.name: [Performance] Remove auto-date table
rules_violated.description:
Avoid using auto-date tables. Make sure to turn off auto-date table in the settings in Power BI Desktop. This will save memory resources. 
Reference: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xu3uDEHtCrg

rules_violated.name: [Formatting] Whole numbers should be formatted with thousands separators and no decimals
[Formatting] Provide format string for measures
rules_violated.description: Visible measures should have their format string property assigned

rules_violated.name: [DAX Expressions] No two measures should have the same DAX expression
rules_violated.description: Two measures with different names and defined by the same DAX expression should be avoided to reduce redundancy.

rules_violated.name: [Formatting] Mark primary keys
rules_violated.description: Set the 'Key' property to 'True' for primary key columns within the column properties.

rules_violated.name: [Formatting] Hide foreign keys
rules_violated.description: Foreign keys should always be hidden.

rules_violated.name: [Formatting] Do not summarize numeric columns
rules_violated.description: Numeric columns (integer, decimal, double) should have their SummarizeBy property set to "None" to avoid accidental summation in Power BI (create measures instead).

rules_violated.name: [Performance] Minimize Power Query transformations
rules_violated.description:
Minimize Power Query transformations in order to improve model processing performance. It is a best practice to offload these transformations to the data warehouse if possible. Also, please check whether query folding is occurring within your model. Please reference the article below for more information on query folding.
Reference: https://docs.microsoft.com/power-query/power-query-folding

rules_violated.name: [Performance] Avoid excessive bi-directional or many-to-many relationships
rules_violated.description:
Limit use of b-di and many-to-many relationships. This rule flags the model if more than 30% of relationships are bi-di or many-to-many.
Reference: https://www.sqlbi.com/articles/bidirectional-relationships-and-ambiguity-in-dax/

rules_violated.name: [Performance] Do not use floating point data types
rules_violated.description: The "Double" floating point data type should be avoided, as it can result in unpredictable roundoff errors and decreased performance in certain scenarios. Use "Int64" or "Decimal" where appropriate (but note that "Decimal" is limited to 4 digits after the decimal sign).

rules_violated.name: [Error Prevention] Data columns must have a source column
rules_violated.description: Data columns must have a source column. A data column without a source column will cause an error when processing the model.

rules_violated.name: [Performance] Avoid bi-directional relationships
rules_violated.description: For best performance, it is recommended to avoid using bi-directional relationships against high-cardinality columns. In order to run this rule, you must first run the script shown here: https://www.elegantbi.com/post/vertipaqintabulareditor
